{'nid': '419671', 'title': '<a href="/history-programs/niels-bohr-library/oral-histories/46715" hreflang="en">Carol Davis</a>', 'field_interview_abstract': '<p>This is an interview with Carol Davis on the occasion of her retirement from 50 years in administrative work at the Department of Physics at Harvard University. Davis reflects on her career, on the support she has provided to students and professors alike, and she explains the ways the department has changed over the years.</p>\n', 'field_additional_persons': '<a href="/content/franklin-melissa-eve-bronwen" hreflang="und">Franklin, Melissa Eve Bronwen</a>, <a href="/content/papaliolios-costas-d" hreflang="en">Papaliolios, Costas D.</a>', 'field_audio_excerpt': '', 'field_bib_number': '46715', 'field_catalog_record': '<a href="https://libserv.aip.org/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=S65N20F144206.1093952&amp;profile=rev-icos&amp;uri=full%3D3100006~%2146715~%210&amp;ri=2&amp;menu=search&amp;source=~%21horizon">See catalog record for this interview.</a>', 'field_has_audio_excerpt': 'No', 'field_institutions': '<a href="/taxonomy/term/2036" hreflang="en">Harvard University</a>', 'field_interview_date': '<time datetime="2020-08-10T12:00:00Z" class="datetime">Mon, 08/10/2020 - 12:00</time>\n', 'field_multiple_dates': '', 'field_interviewer': 'David Zierler', 'field_interviewee_image': '', 'field_interviewee_image_2': '\n            <div class="field field--name-field-media-image field--type-image field--label-hidden field__item"><a href="/sites/default/files/2022-05/Davis%20credit%20%20Torrence%20Davis.jpg" class="file-download file-download-image file-download-jpeg" target="_blank" download>Download</a></div>\n      ', 'field_interviewee_image_2_credit': '<p>Credit: Torrence Davis</p>\n', 'field_interviewee_name': 'Davis, Carol', 'field_interview_location': 'Video conference', 'field_image_name_authority': '<a href="/content/davis-carol" hreflang="en">Davis, Carol</a>', 'field_preferred_citation': '<div class="field-group-format-wrapper" style="display: block;">\n<div class="field field-name-field-preferred-citation field-type-text-long field-label-hidden">\n<div class="field-items">\n<div class="field-item even">\n<p>In footnotes or endnotes please cite AIP interviews like this:</p>\n<p>Interview of Carol Davis by David Zierler on August 10, 2020,<br />\nNiels Bohr Library &amp; Archives, American Institute of Physics,<br />\nCollege Park, MD USA,<br /><a href="http://www.aip.org/history-programs/niels-bohr-library/oral-histories/46715">www.aip.org/history-programs/niels-bohr-library/oral-histories/46715</a></p>\n<p>For multiple citations, "AIP" is the preferred abbreviation for the location.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n', 'field_related_audio': '', 'field_related_images': '', 'field_single_or_first_session': 'Single session', 'field_subjects': '<a href="/taxonomy/term/12666" hreflang="en">Administrative assistants</a>, <a href="/taxonomy/term/12671" hreflang="en">College administrators</a>, <a href="/taxonomy/term/11306" hreflang="en">Diversity in higher education</a>, <a href="/taxonomy/term/9501" hreflang="en">Race relations</a>, <a href="/taxonomy/term/12676" hreflang="en">Science education -- Administration</a>', 'body': "<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Okay. This is David Zierler, oral historian for the American Institute of Physics. It is August 10th, 2020. I am so happy to be here with Carol Davis. Carol, thank you so much for joining me today.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>You're welcome. My pleasure.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>All right. So, to start, would you tell me your title and your institutional affiliation?</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>My title is graduate and undergraduate student coordinator. It started out as the undergraduate student coordinator, but they added graduate to the title, since I dealt with some of the graduate student aspects of the position.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>So, you just started as undergraduate student coordinator in physics and then you did such a good job, they just decided to double your portfolio and give you graduate students also?</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>Well, the graduate administrator had her hands full. And I would always ask if help was needed to fill in some of the free time I had. When this position was created by Professor Melissa Franklin, who was Chairperson at the time, we weren't sure what all of the duties were going to be, we definitely knew what some of the duties were going to be, but they were not enough for a full-time position, so adding some of the graduate student duties helped to make it a full-time position.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>As time went on, more duties were added. And the first thing that I kind of figured out was, when I worked with Melissa as a faculty assistant or technical secretary, as they called it way back, she taught a lot of undergraduate classes. Therefore, lot of students would come in looking for Professor Franklin’s advice during her office and there were times when she wasn't there. So, I took it upon myself to get to know the students while they were waiting for her. I'm very people curious anyway. So, I would always ask questions like, where they were from, what they do outside of physics, any special talents, are they in a relationship, if they like physics, are they're going to continue, whatever. But a lot of the students and I became friends. There was a point in time when students entered the office and Melissa would say, “oh, are you here to see me?” And they would answer, “no, I'm here to see Carol!” (laughter)</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Carol, how did you get to Harvard originally? Are you from the Boston area?</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>Well, it's hard to say. I was born in Evanston, Illinois. My parents worked in Evanston. A year later and they moved to Pittsburgh. A year after that they moved to Cambridge, Massachusetts. And I lived in Cambridge, up until I was eleven years old, when my mother became ill and we didn't think that she was going to have long to live. And my father felt that he couldn't take care of his three daughters. So, he moved us back to Pittsburgh to live with his brother and his wife. And I stayed there until I graduated in high school. I wasn’t a big fan of Pittsburg and left the day after I graduated high school. I came back to Cambridge, actually Medford, about fifteen minutes away, and haven’t left since. But I still have very close friends that I am in contact with from Pittsburgh.</p>\n<p>After growing up in such a strict home life, you know, I just went hog wild. I was finally able to come and go as I pleased. I came back and I ended up having a child when I was twenty years old. And as I lay in my room, all that time taking care of this new little beautiful boy, thinking about what I was going to do to support him, I always listened to a radio station, WILD, that always advertised, come to Harvard for a job, an equal opportunity employer. And, you know what? When it was time to find a job, it was already in my head, go to Harvard. So, I went to Harvard University, sixth floor, Holyoke Center and I took a typing test. I passed with flying colors, and they sent me straight to the Physics Department. And before I left that day, I had a job. Nothing like today (laughter). You don't see anybody today; it’s mostly done with resumes and phone calls. But in a manner of three hours, from test to interview, I had a job in the Physics Department at Harvard University.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And, Carol, what year was that?</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>That was 1970.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>1970</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>My son was five months old when I started working.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>So, we're saying now, this is a fifty-year anniversary if my math is correct.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>Yes, yes.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Amazing.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>September 7, I think is the end of the fiftieth year.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>I'm looking at you right now. I don't believe fifty years. I don't know. I'm going to have to check the chronology here.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>You know what, students say that all the time. I always ask the students, “how old are you”? And then I say, oh my Goodness, you could be my great grandchild. They're like, no. And I'm like, yeah, I could. We get into arguments about that all the time. You know, even the parents, they come in to meet me and they're totally surprised at how old I am.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>So, who actually hired you in the department?</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>His name was Dr. Preston. He was the director of the laboratory back then. And he asked questions like if my son became ill, who was going to take care of him? Because he didn’t want me to miss work, right? He asked me how old I was. You know, things that they're not allowed to ask today. So, I was really surprised. I didn't even know anything about physics, even though at my high school, my homeroom teacher was a physicist. His name was Mr. Halperin and he taught the physics courses, but I never took it. I actually took the business courses, where we were taught things like typing, shorthand, accounting, economics, courses associated with business training. So, I guess I fell into what I thought I was going to do.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Now physically, were you always in the same building or you moved around over the years?</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>I have always been in the same building but with four different positions.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>So, what was the first job?</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>The first job was a clerical typist.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And what kind of work would you do in that job? What would you be do?</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>I worked for the library. And, I would do all the mimeographing and copying for all the courses. All the courses were taught in our building before the new Cabot library and Science Center were built, which houses a lot of our undergrad courses now. Professors would bring everything up to me to mimeograph and to Xerox and collate and put all the coursework together. And believe me, It wasn’t an exciting job. I absolutely hated it. I ended up staying in that job for only three months. I became friends with the assistant to the secretary of the chairman in the chairman's office, we actually started working at Harvard in the department at the same time and she was ready to give up her job, which she didn’t like. So, after three months, she left and I applied for her job. I would always tell her that her position was what I was looking for.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Why, Carol? What did you see in that job that was attractive to you or what lined up with your skills?</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>Well, number one, I got to see students or just people. Number two, I dealt with keeping the undergraduate records up to date and setting up qualifying orals and Ph.D. defenses, making appointments, greeting visitors, typing recommendations, etc. It was the variety of things that I had to take care of daily that made the job interesting. And if I remember correctly, I was also working for four assistant professors directly. So, they would come in my office if they needed anything. And I would help the assistant to the chairman with anything that she needed my help with. And he turned out to be one of the faculty members that I work for almost up until the day he left the department.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And who was that, Carol?</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>That was Professor Pound. And he was one of the professors that I admired, and I loved. He would keep a couple of us who worked in the office, after work till six o'clock or longer, just talking. Talking about his cars, his child, any lessons he was taking; he was learning how to fly a plane and drive a motorcycle. He would find something to talk about. And, up until the day he left the department, because I was practically one of the only staff members he still knew, since I had been there so long. He would come to my office to get me to do little things for him. And I would still get to hear those stories.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Like what, Carol, give me a good story that illustrates this relationship.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>(Laughter) Okay. One of the stories that I remember in those late years which helped me to understand how comfortable he was with me was on this particular day he came in, like usual and had we had our normal greeting, how are you doing today? How are things? How are you feeling, etc. “Oh, I have to go have a blood test tomorrow. It's driving me crazy that I have to do this every once in a while.” He had some sort of ailment that he had to go have blood tests every now and then. And I said, oh, that's sad. Hopefully they'll figure it out and get you fixed up. He said, “I just came from New York and he didn’t know why I drove.” I said, I know, that's a long drive. You know, for someone of his age, right? He said, “oh, my God, I got to Connecticut and the traffic was so, backed up. And he said, I had to pee so bad” (laughter). He said, “I didn't know where I was going to stop.” He's like, the traffic was terrible, He eventually made it and was able to stop and take care of that problem! .</p>\n<p>And I'm sitting there thinking, okay, clearly this man is really comfortable with me, right? But it was funny. That was one of the stories. We always talked about his cars because I loved his car. He drove a Rolls-Royce and he had a Jag, which I always loved. You know, I'm so high end (laughter). He took airplane lessons and took motorcycle lessons, which he didn't pass at first. So, it was little things like that which he would he would talk to me about. He was a great talker and I always listened patiently and enjoyed his stories.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Carol, in this job, what were some of the things that you did that were really lifesavers for the professors? What would you do that they needed you so badly, they couldn't do anything without you?</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>Lie (laughter). Just lie, lie, lie. Appointments that they didn't want to go to, you know. Or I'm not in office right now. We did a lot of personal things for people back then, like taking their books back to the library. Even taking their wives' books back to the library. Faculty assistants today wouldn’t think of doing that and probably wouldn't be asked to do that today.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>Because it's too personal. I have taken care of quite a few babies and children during appointments and meetings. I remember one Professor brought his son into me one day, who did not even have a diaper on. And he's like, Carol, I have to go to a meeting, can you just watch him for a little bit? I said to him, I hope you have diapers (laughter). And he threw those down, and he left. What else could I do? I did a lot of that, A lot of baby watching. But you know it kind of made the job a lot more fun and got you away from all the other stresses and I actually loved hanging out with the kids. Some of these kids still come in to see me, which means I made some sort of impact on their lives, especially if they take time to come see me at the office.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>And what about for students, Carol? What kind of things would you do for students that they could never do on their own?</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>I typed their theses. I typed lots of them, lots of them. I spent many of my spring months lugging my typewriter home from my office, to my kitchen table. I would come home, and I would make dinner. I'd feed my son. I'd give him a bath. Put him to bed. Clean up the kitchen. Turn the radio on with some good music and start typing. I would type until three or four o'clock in the morning.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Oh, man.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>The next morning, I'd take that typewriter back to work and I'd sit there and do my work. At lunch time I'd work on the thesis some more. Students weren’t using computers and typing their own theses in those days, so, I would get a handwritten version of their thesis and I would type it with all those handwritten equations. I would miss parts of April and mostly all of May typing those things round the clock. I think that's what they needed most. We would also arrange events, like taking them to plays or just arranging dinners to get them away from all the studying.</p>\n<p>Today, I think they need me just for a hug or for a comforting conversation. I didn't give many hugs, back in the day. I'm finding students need them more today. I think it's a little bit harder, for them for some reason or another. Whether they can’t get in touch with their advisor, girlfriend, boyfriend problems, grade problems or they don't think that they are up to the level of the next student, which makes me sad because I always have to tell them they all got here to Harvard University the same way. I mean, I've sat in an admissions meeting. I say, you got here the same way. You filled out an application just like everyone else did.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>They wouldn't have chosen you if they didn't see something in you and felt that you were Harvard material. So, don't think like that. It's really hard sometimes to convince some students that they are just as smart as the next student.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>That's important to note that even Harvard students sometimes struggle with confidence issues.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>Of course. I mean, people outside of Harvard wouldn't think that, but they do. I've cried with many a student because of that, because it just saddens my heart that they're so insecure when they have come so far to become a Harvard graduate student, you know. I never really had that opportunity, but I've learned a lot from these students. So, I am very sad to be leaving them. I always wanted to keep their spirits lifted and let them know that if there is no one else, that I was always proud of them.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>It's so funny because I often get emotional when I started talking about the students. I love every one of them. And I tell them now, it's really hard for me to see what's going on in the world and I felt so bad that these students couldn't have ended out the year with the pomp and circumstance that they worked so hard for. It doesn’t seem like there was any closure.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right. Right.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>And me not being able to even meet their parents and tell them how proud I have been of all of them. I tend to see graduate students more than undergrads because they basically live in the building in their offices and laboratories. The undergraduates I see in the morning, or when they find out I have shitloads of candy in my office (laughter). Sorry. I feel like I'm in my office, so I can tell you that, every student that comes in my office and closes the door, I tell them that this is like Vegas. What happens in Carol's office stays in Carol's office.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And I bet they tell you all kinds of things that they would never tell anyone else.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>You wouldn't believe. I tell them, I tend to have a potty mouth. If that offends you, let me know. I know when I can use it and when I can't. And it probably won't be used until I get to know you better (laughter).But sometimes it slips. And I think it comes from working with Melissa all those years (laughter)! I said a bad word one day, and I did not realize she was in her office. But I had made a mistake on something and I just went, ahh, F%$#K!</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>And Melissa said , “Carol, did you just say, F%#k’? I said, “Oh, my goodness, Melissa, I didn't realize you were in there. I'm so, so sorry.” She said, “no, that's not it.” She said, “I've just never heard you use that kind of language before.” And she said, “you don't talk like that when I'm around.” I said, “well, Melissa, my office is right by the front door.” I said, “Deans walk past this door. The President of the University may walk past. Even other faculty members, that I respect walk past this door, and I wouldn't want them to hear me say anything like that.” I said, “that was a slip, believe me, but you probably won't hear me saying that again unless we're speaking privately.”</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>So, we understood each other. Melissa and I are almost alike. And I think a lot of the faculty assistants say, they could not work for Melissa. I said, no, Melissa is nothing like what you see. You know, I've seen her high points, I've seen her low points. And I said, we've been friends for many years. And she introduces me as a friend. And I feel the same way about her, you know. And I wouldn't have had this job if it weren't for her.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Now, Carol, when did you get into your third position at Harvard? You said there were four overall.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>Third position. Did I say four? Well, the third one was, oh, the first one was the-</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Clerical typist.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>The second one was the assistant to the chairman's assistant (laughter). I should say assistant to the department secretary because that's what she was called back then.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>The third job was technical secretary working for people like Professor Purcell, Professor Ramsey, Professor Pipkin, Professor Horowitz and Professor Pound. Both Norman Ramsey and Edward Purcell were Nobel Prize Winners. Well, I didn't work for Professor Pound there, but mostly Professor Ramsey, Professor Horowitz and Professor Pipkin. When Professor Purcell's assistant retired, I took him on. When Melissa joined the department as an Assistant Professor, I started working for her. There were many others in between or after that. I worked for all the older professors like Professor Street and Professor Papaliolios who I admired. And I miss him so dearly. He was one of those professors who actually knew my father, since my father worked at Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory. And he didn't connect this until he saw my father in my office one day. He was a little surprised that we were related and never knew it.</p>\n<p>But we had we had hung out before. He would come into my office and he would say, Carol, I got a new car. And I would say, oh, what did you get? And he'd say something weird like a Lamborghini. I really didn’t know what kind it was just some little expensive sportscar. He said come take a ride. And I said, I can't go. He would say, come on, just tell them you're doing something for a Professor. I said, alright. So, we'd get in the car and we'd drive up to Lincoln or Sudbury and we'd just check out how the car drove talk about the weather, or what was happening in the Department and other things, but definitely not physics! He never had a Faculty Assistant, don’t think he really needed one, but if he had anything that he needed, he would stop by my office and ask me to do it.</p>\n<p>But I really, really miss him. I was the only staff member that was actually invited to his retirement party, which he didn't want to have. But Professor Paul Horowitz, who is a good friend of his, said that he had to have a retirement party and planned it for him. And I always used to tease Paul because, of course, I was the only person of color there, since this was some time ago, and I would say to Paul, “if anybody asks me to take their coat and hat, I'm going to smack you.” We would just laugh, he knew I was joking.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right. Good for you.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>(Laughter) Paul understood me, since he was one of the Professors I first started working for in 1973 and did almost up until maybe about five years before he retired. Professor Horowitz still drops by my office for a sweet treat or a Diet Coke now and then and we still catch up on all the gossip around the department.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>But, going back, you know, you might find out, I'm one of these people that start a conversation and hit three other topics before I get back to the first conversation. And, what I was going to say to you was that being the only person of color in that department for almost fifteen years, it never bothered me. I never paid any attention to it because I'm comfortable in my own color and skin. I'm comfortable with who I am. Until somebody says something that makes me think about who I am. And, I just told someone the other day that the reason for that is because I've worked in a department with people and kids from all over the world who don't make any differences with who I am. They have never made me feel different. And I feel the same way about them. With what's been going on in the past five months, I have really thought about who I am. And I've never been more aware of my blackness than I have in the past five months. Some of the things that have been going on in our country wakes you up to who you are and where you fit in, makes me think about my color so much more than I ever have before.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Wow.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>I've had every student, so many students, email me and ask me how I'm doing, if I'm okay, and they just don’t know how much I appreciate their concern.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Oh, that's so nice.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>I miss their hugs, you know. And I cry every time I hear from them because I miss them so, so much. It's just strange, I would have five or six students in my office at the time, just talking about anything, you know, whether it's their advisors, whether it's their exams or grades, etc. and I think that's the reason why Melissa wanted me to have this job.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Now, what is this job? What's the job that Melissa wanted you to have?</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>The fourth job is undergraduate and graduate student coordinator.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right. Now, Carol, in what ways was this job a promotion or a step up or recognition for all the amazing work you had been doing over the years?</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>I think Melissa saw the kinds of connections I had with students. And she felt that our department needed that. They needed someone that they could just come to and speak to without worrying about anyone passing judgement. Someone they could feel comfortable with. And I think it works. I think Melissa would have to give you the real reason she wanted me in that position. But I think from the amount of students that visit my office on a daily basis, shows that someone with Motherly arms is needed!</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>Someone that would speak straight to them. Which is me. Because, you know, I was raised in the streets, basically (laughter).</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>I can talk to the best to them and I can talk to the worst of them, you know. And, I definitely can say my street side and school of hard knocks comes out in my conversations with students. And they mock me a lot. You know, they're like, girl, what did I tell you about… And they do that so much and it does not offend me because they know what type of person I am. You know, if I am ever offended, I will definitely speak up right away. I definitely will forgive you at some point, but I will not ever forget it. And the students know it. I think they have my trust and I have theirs. I think there has been one time that I kind of hurt one student by saying something that I should not have said but, I was really, really worried about this student. And that hurt me to my core because in my job, I know that I'm not a therapist, I know I'm not a counselor. I tell everybody that. I said the first thing I'm a mother, I'm a grandmother, I'm even a great grandmother, I'm a sister, and I'm a wife. I said, if anyone has any problem, that's the role I take on. I look into their heart and eyes to see what's bothering them and I try to fix it or make them feel better. Sometimes it can't be fixed, you know, but at least I want them to know that I care, that somebody cares about them. They can't be with their mother and, sometimes they can't tell a fellow student what's bothering them. You know? Maybe they don't want to show somebody else their insecurities, but they always seem to be comfortable with me.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>And I always want them to be comfortable. And that was the one and only time. And it still bothers me today. You know, we've moved on, the student and I and I think he is in a much better place than that day, but I cannot look at him without thinking how much I possibly could have failed him. And that really still bothers me.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>I think that really speaks to, you know, all of the care and love you've given over the years and how if there was one incident that really wasn't even your fault, how upsetting it is to you. I just think that that really speaks to your character and just how much you care for everybody around you.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>I do. I really do. I mean, even faculty matters. You know, I care so much for Melissa and some of the other faculty I practically grew up with. My husband goes to the Penn Relays with one of the faculty members every year. I always tell him that's my one weekend to just hang out without him so keep taking him away. He laughs at that (laughter).</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Carol, you've talked so beautifully about how you've supported so many people over the years. I want to ask you, in terms of the professors, who over the past fifty years really stands out in your memory among the faculty as the people who have supported you? Who have championed you, who have been there to give you a shoulder to cry on when you needed it? When you needed support, when you needed encouragement, who among the faculty really jumps out in your mind as really being there for you?</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>You know, there's a few professors that have been there for me. But first and foremost, it would be Melissa Franklin. I worked for her at least twenty-five years and Melissa has done so much for me that I can't raise her high enough. I can't say that there wasn't any kind of racial discrimination in that department towards me from certain administrators in the past. But she took care of those problems for me. If it were up to them, I probably would have been fired. Just out of pure jealousy or their own insecurities. She is one of the Faculty Members that truly cares about the staff and they all love her.</p>\n<p>It makes me happy that my office was a kind of go to when students were bored, or faculty needed a laugh or staff needed a shoulder. They all would come right into my office and we would sit right down and figure out the problems of the world. I’m going to miss those days so much. Especially the laughter, there was always so much laughter coming out of my office and it’s kept me young at heart. The staff that I work with are the best people anyone could have around them on a daily basis, they are the type of people that lift you up and never pull you down.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>I don't think that these women, and I'm saying women because we don't have male faculty assistants right now, they go through so much for their faculty and are asked to do so much more than we were asked to do a long time ago. I have been blessed to work with such intelligent and personable women who truly care about each other.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Sure.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>And it's hard for them sometimes to take on the faculty stress and it makes them more stressed out. And then to have administrators limiting you as to what you can do and what you can’t, and I’m generalizing here. I've been told by administrators that I'm not a therapist. I'm not a psychologist. And, you know what, I told them just what I told you. And I told him there's no way, short of firing me, that you're going to stop these students coming to see me. And of course, you know, all these girls are women younger than me. And they'll always say, well Carol, you can do that. Well, Carol, you can say that. And I say to them, you can say it, too. I said, do you think I just started saying these things at the age of seventy? No. I started saying these when I was twenty-two because I wasn't going to let anyone run it over me and tell me what I could and couldn't do. Period.</p>\n<p>I’ve learned that sometimes you need to go to the top to get things done. It’s okay to bypass the middleman to have your voice heard. There have been times where I have gotten into arguments with people above me that haven’t ended well. I’ve had to be spoken to about things like this, and it means more to me coming from the person it affects than someone else. That means a lot, the professionalism to tackle tough things head on.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Carol, what do you think you learned about yourself from this from this episode?</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>I always knew. I didn't just learn it. I always knew that I was going to defend myself whatever, with whomever. If you're going to come at me with bad intentions, I'm going to straighten it out right there. I don't need an e-mail. I don't need a letter. We're going to meet face to face, head on. And we're going to take good care of it. You are going to know right from me how I feel about what you did. And maybe you'll think about it the next time. I may not be right every time, but if I'm in your face telling you you're wrong, you're wrong. That's how I feel (laughter).</p>\n<p>And I'm telling you, if I'm wrong, I will absolutely say I'm sorry. I apologize. I shouldn't have done it. One faculty assistant had butted into a conversation one day, and he reminded me some months later that I didn't talk to him for three months. I said, that's me. I can do that. I felt at that moment I didn't need you in my life. You didn't do anything to affect my life. So, I kept you out. Eventually, we started talking again and I laughed about that. I said, well, now you know who I am. You butted into my business, and you won't do it again. And that's who I am.</p>\n<p>And, you know, I don't think of myself as a tough person. There are students who actually come to my office for the first time shaking. Because they don't know who I am or what I'm going to be like. And I know it's because I'm a large woman. I'm five foot nine. I have a big voice and they hear it. And they're literally almost afraid. And I like playing on that, because I notice it right off. You know, it's like, “what are you doing standing out in the hall? Come in. You want to ask a question? Open your mouth and ask it” (laughter).</p>\n<p>And they look at me. And I say, “I can't hear you.” You know, because there are so many students that are so meek and mild. And I tell them, you come to some professor's office with that little voice, they will never hear you. They will never see you. Open your mouth. By the time they leave my office, I mean, not that day, but by the end of the four years, they're in my office laughing and joking. They're loud. They don't care anymore. They say what they feel. And that's what I want them to do.</p>\n<p>Even when a parent shows up to check out the department with his son or daughter and the parent is doing all the talking. I will ask the parent if they are the ones applying to Harvard? And then I look at the student and let them know that Mom and Dad will not be here to answer all of your questions for you while you are attending school. I tell the parent to have a seat and get them some water or whatever they need and let their child do the talking! It works! Got to start them somewhere.</p>\n<p>You know, it's like even when I get a handshake, I get a little mealy handshake. I say, oh, that handshake told me a lot about you. I said, are you just weak minded and wimpy. And, I said, if you got to shake the king's hand for that Noble Prize, is it going to be a little teeny-weeny handshake like that? And they laughed. So, I say, do it again. Grab my hand and make it firm this time.</p>\n<p>And every time I see them, I shake their hand. That's the way I want to see it, you know. I tell them, I said I'm not academically smart. I said, I'm street smart. And I said, do you think that I would be able to sit in a room, the only person of color who knows nothing about physics with Nobel laureates asking me to sit at their table, if I weren't the person that I was? And I ask myself, who the hell am I and how did I get here? But it makes you feel good that you can sit with people from any kind of surroundings and feel comfortable. And that's what I want these students to feel wherever they go, you know? And I think it works. I hope it works.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Carol, over fifty years, there's, I mean, there's so many things that have changed. I want to ask you about a few of them retrospectively. First, I'd like to ask is about technology, right? In 1970, we're talking about rotary telephones and typewriters. And today we're talking about iPhones and laptops and everything else, right? So, I want to hear your take on how technology has changed the fundamentals of what you do and how technology has not changed the fundamentals of what you do.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>Okay, let me start with technology changing things. First, well, a lot of it has made things a lot easier. You know, I can carry this little phone around with me and get a call anywhere in the world now.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>I can look at my e-mail. Which is, could be a plus or a minus.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yes, exactly. It goes both ways.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>Right. I can see your face because we're having this conversation on our computers. And I often think of my father who worked Smithsonian's Astrophysical Observatory on computers. And he would be amazed at this technology if he were alive today. Besides the fact that Obama was president. He would be totally amazed.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>I remember when he first got his computer, he called me up to ask me about this software. It was called Volkswriter. And that's what we used to type the first equations on the computer. That's where you would leave spaces for everything and go back and fill them in. And I tell these girls today, I say, what are you doing today is nothing. I said, what we did back in the day was a skill. You really had to learn and know what you were doing to make a paper or article look good and we completed all the publications on a typewriter then.</p>\n<p>I thought I'd never use the cell phone. I thought I'd never get e-mail on my cell phone. My son works in IT for National Grid, which is the electricity company for Massachusetts. He deals with all the computers on the trucks and things like that. It's the first job he's had in his thirty years that he actually loves. You don't know how happy I am that he doesn't come home, and I say, oh, how was your day? It sucked (laughter). He doesn't say that anymore so I'm happy about that.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>That's great.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>So that's the one thing. I don't have to type theses anymore. The students do their own, which is so much easier. Although I miss the money that I used to make from typing them, I’m so happy that I get to see spring. I never did back in the day. I love the fact that we can correct things so much easier on a computer. And I can do banking. We can do banking all of our on a computer. The downside is we don't get to see people anymore. And our younger generations are happy with that! Socially, nothing is done without a phone or a computer. Face to face social contact is gone!</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Yeah.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>That is the worst thing. People don't even see each other face to face, I mean, like even with the interview process. I used to be able to walk into the building, take my typing test, walk over to physics, meet the people I'm going to work with and know that day whether I have a job or not. Today, people are waiting months before they find out, after five different types of telephone interviews, if they have a job. I swear, a business could fail before you get hired to even work there. I never understood that. And I still don't understand that.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>I mean, I could tell just from looking at you that I would hire you. Just on your appearance alone. Your pleasant smile, your eyes, how you even feel about the way I'm answering the questions you are asking. You know, you can't tell that over the phone.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>I have told some staff that. Sometimes they've said certain things to me, like, I don't know, Carol, there might be red flags. I said, how in the hell can you tell? You've just been on a phone, you know. I said, give this person a chance. You have three months to decide whether you want them to work here or not. That's the most telling way of finding out if you want this person. And, if she or he fits in with everybody else. And that's one thing that that even today now that I do that we couldn't do. You know, a new person is being hired, I would always go and say, we need to meet them. We need to sit down and talk to them without any managers. And we did. You know, I would make quiche, and we'd come in and we'd sit down, and we'd have a chat with this person. And we'd tell them, you know, okay, you're on stage. We're here to find out if you're going to fit in. Not that it's that kind of place. But we all want to work well together. So far there hasn’t been anyone we gave bad marks to, just for the record!</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>And I want you to be able to work well with us as we are working with you. And so, we ask her or him dumb questions. And my first question is always, tell me a joke and then what was the last movie you saw or book you read, it can tell you a lot! Then, ask us anything you couldn't ask people who were in charge of hiring. Ask us anything. And they do.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>They ask us questions like, what do you think about the person who's interviewing? How is it working here, how is the moral and we answer truthfully, I think it's only fair that we not only know them, but they know about us.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right. Carol, other big question I wanted to ask you, you know, reflecting back on your fifty year something that really jumped out at me. You know, you said over the past three months you've never been so aware of your identity before. Right? And, so, my big overall question there is, you know, looking back on this incredible tenure and thinking about, you know, nowadays where the science community really needs to think hard about how to improve diversity and inclusivity and civility and all of these things, right? That really should have been improved much longer ago than dealing with this right now.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>I agree.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>I want to ask you, looking back from 1970 to today, what are some challenges that you've seen from your vantage point in the Department of Physics that have gotten better over time? And what are some areas that really still need fundamental opportunities for improvement?</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>There is always room for improvement. In fact, I had a talk with our Chairman the other day. First of all, there were hardly ever graduate students of color in the department in the seventies. And, slowly, one or two. And I got to know them all, of course, you know, because I'm the one that they felt comfortable with. I would love it if they felt comfortable with everyone in the department. But I've heard many stories and not just from the Physics Department that some students don't think that students of color, and I'm just generalizing here, not pointing anyone out, know as much or are as smart, nothing in my lifetime, I have never heard before. We had one administrator tell one student of color, well, you know how you got here. I did not hear about this until after they had left, but if I had, I definitely would have said something.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>Maybe not to the powers that be, but I would have gone directly to her or him.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>To tell them that it's possible you can lose your job for saying something like that. You know, you do not say things like that to any student, especially if you're the graduate administrator. These days we are seeing, more students of color in the department. And I'm happy for them.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>It sounds like it's not happening fast enough.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>No, not to me. But it is getting better. It would have been nice to have all these open forums for discussion years ago. Since I received this position, the graduate administrator that I was working with took ill the first year I got this job. And she always attended the Society of Black Physicists conference. And the first time I went, I went in her place because she couldn't go and I was thinking, what am I going to do? I didn't know anything about graduate admissions, I didn't know how it worked. We had a couple other people, we had the Associate Director of Graduate Studies come along, who answered a lot of those questions I couldn’t answer. And I think a professor, I think Melissa was there, no maybe Professor Manoharan. So, the very first day, in Austin, Texas, today has reminded me of it. It was so hot. It was pathetic, I thought I was going to die in that heat, made me cross Texas off of my list of places to visit!</p>\n<p>The first day was registration, oh, and it was actually the Society of Black and Hispanic Physicists and I was in awe of how many African American and Hispanic students were at this conference. I was like, oh, my!</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Maybe there's a bigger world out there beyond Harvard?</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>Yes. Yes. And maybe Yale and Princeton and MIT. [Laughs] But I'm not there, I'm just at Harvard. And before I knew I was talking to all these students and finding out that, oh- and I have to tell you, it was my first time there and everyone was setting up tables and putting their little giveaways out. And I would be saying hello to all of them, you know, and a lot of them weren't people of color. Illinois, Stanford, MIT, Penn, Columbia, Boston University, etc. I was just joking and talking with them trying to get comfortable in these new surroundings, you know, and found out most of them did the job that I did. And the minute my Harvard banner went up, they were like, oh, you work at Harvard? I said, don't say that. It was almost like because I was from Harvard, I was thinking I was better than them! That was the feeling I got, you know Harvard has a reputation! (laughter)</p>\n<p>I said, I don’t know what you are thinking but, Harvard is the same as any other school here. I said, look, they sent me. And that's what I said. And over the years, I've met a lot of students, a lot of staff and some of the faculty that have been going to this conference because now I've been going to them for the past six or seven or maybe eight years. I can't remember. And I've even seen some of the former Harvard graduate students there. Which was nice, you know, because I still keep in contact with a lot of the students that have graduated.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Right.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>I said, what I would like you to do for me is that in the past six years that I have gone to the NSBP, I can count on one hand how many of our faculty members have attended that conference. I want you to make sure that there are more faculty members that give up a little of their time and go to that conference. So, they have no excuses why we don't have more students of color.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>And how was that suggestion received, Carol?</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>Very well by the new chairman. I said, that's the only promise I'm asking you. I said, you have to understand they're undergraduates there looking to get into graduate school. There are graduate students looking for postdoc positions. There are postdocs there looking for faculty positions. And if we have our faculty there, networking and seeing what's out there, as not to embarrass Harvard by one faculty member showing up. That would make me feel very happy.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Carol, that's such an extraordinarily important thing that you did. And it demonstrates that your legacy in the department really gets to the core of making the department a better place to be. So, I'm so glad that you were able to- I'm so glad you were able to share that with me and that this is such an important part of the historical record.</p>\n<p>Carol, I want to ask for my last question, you know, it's so obvious, from talking to Melissa, from hearing from you, the department has a lot of work to do because it's never going to be able to replace you. And it's never going to be the same department after this remarkable five-decade legacy that you've left. And so, the big question is what they're going to do. But the smaller question is, what are you looking forward to in retirement? What do you want to do and how do you want to enjoy yourself, looking ahead in your own life now?</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>Well, my husband's been retired for some time. He was young and he had bypass surgery at a young age. He worked in construction. So, he really couldn't do that anymore. So, he's been home all these years. God bless him. I've had a bout with breast cancer and this man got up every morning to drive me into Boston, for my radiation treatments and back to Harvard for six weeks without fail and I am happy to say I have been cancer free for ten years. We've been together almost forty-eight years. We've battled with each other laughed and cried with each other, but you can imagine I don't take crap from him. And he's the same way. He's the scorpion, I'm type A Taurean, and I love him dearly, but he has his life. I have my life. We have our life. I travel a lot more than he does. My sisters live in California. And we have been living so far apart since, I think, we were all at the age of eighteen. They've always been somewhere else. My sisters have lived together since they were probably teens, one was in the Army, one was in the Navy. And when they got out of the service, they live with each other because they were both single and I was married. So, I visit them every year. We do road trips all the time, you know. The last road trip we took, we drove from California to Oregon to Seattle into Canada and back to California into Nevada. And we hung out there for a little while. But we all love to travel together, so we make sure that we all get together. My sister is trying to find out what they're doing for my retirement so she can come, I tell them it's not that important.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>It is important.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>I said, I don't even know if we're going to be together. It might be a Zoom or something. Who knows? But she's planning to be here because she has to be involved with every aspect of my life.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Carol, at the right time, you're going to have a retirement party when people can see each other again that is befitting of the legacy that you have left.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>I hope so.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Carol, I'm so glad that we connected. I'm not part of the Harvard physics faculty, but I've interviewed so many of them, and, so, I understand not only what a special place it is, but how central you have been to making it that central place. So, I want to thank you for the time that we've spent together. And most importantly, I want you to enjoy your retirement because it's a retirement that is well earned.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>Oh, I definitely will.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>So, thank you so much.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>I enjoy each day to its fullest.</p>\n<h3>Zierler:</h3>\n<p>Okay.</p>\n<h3>Davis:</h3>\n<p>It's nice meeting you.</p>\n"}